  "signature": "ed25519:9b1d3f5a7c2e4b6d8f0a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0d2f4a6c8e0b2d4f6a8c0e2b4d",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) must hold a current ISO 9001 certificate and a documented SQA plan covering version control, regression testing, and change management. All three FEA codes in the ensemble must pass the ASME V&V 10.1 benchmark suite with residuals below 1e-6.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is used under an ISO 9001:2015-certified quality management system. Version control is enforced via Git with mandatory peer review prior to merge. Automated regression tests covering 47 benchmark cases are executed on every release candidate; all cases pass with normalized residuals below 1e-6. The FDA in-house code and DePuy Synthes solver carry equivalent SQA documentation, verified during the inter-laboratory coordination meeting in Q3 2023."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Each solver in the ensemble must demonstrate second-order spatial convergence on at least three canonical structural benchmarks (patch test, cantilever beam, Hertzian contact). Observed order of accuracy must be within 10% of theoretical.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions and three canonical benchmarks: a linear elastic patch test, an Euler-Bernoulli cantilever beam under tip load, and a Hertzian sphere-on-flat contact problem. All three solvers achieved observed orders of accuracy between 1.94 and 2.08, within 10% of the theoretical second-order rate. Results are archived in the verification report VR-COU1-2023-09."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Discretization error must be estimated via Richardson extrapolation across at least three mesh densities. The grid convergence index (GCI) for each QoI must be below 2% on the production mesh.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with element edge lengths of 1.0 mm, 0.5 mm, and 0.25 mm in the screw-rod interface region. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.3%, 0.9%, and 1.7% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement, respectively, all below the 2% threshold. The production mesh uses the 0.5 mm density as the best compromise between accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge to below 1e-8 for all load steps. Contact penetration must not exceed 1e-4 mm at any interface node.",
      "rationale": "The direct sparse solver (PARDISO) is used for all linear solution steps; iterative residuals are not applicable in direct mode. Contact penetration at the screw-rod and rod-vertebral body block interfaces was monitored across all 11 experimental replicate simulations; maximum nodal penetration was 3.2e-5 mm, well within the 1e-4 mm limit. Solver log files are archived in the simulation package SP-COU1-2023."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All simulation inputs must be reviewed by a second qualified analyst before execution. A documented simulation execution checklist must be completed and signed for each model run.",
      "rationale": "A two-analyst review protocol was implemented: the primary analyst prepared boundary conditions, material assignments, and load definitions, and a second analyst independently verified each against the ASTM F1717 test protocol and the experimental setup documentation before any simulation was executed. A 34-item checklist was completed and co-signed for each of the 11 replicate simulations. No use errors were identified during the review cycle."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The model must capture nonlinear geometric effects (large-displacement formulation) and frictional contact at all metal-metal interfaces. Constitutive model selection must be justified against published material coupon data for Ti-6Al-4V ELI.",
      "rationale": "A nonlinear large-displacement formulation (Updated Lagrangian) is used throughout. Frictional contact (Coulomb, mu=0.2) is applied at the screw-rod set-screw interface and at the rod-UHMWPE block interface. The bilinear isotropic hardening model for Ti-6Al-4V ELI was calibrated against coupon tensile data from the same material lot used to manufacture the test constructs; yield stress 880 MPa, tangent modulus 1.2 GPa, consistent with ASTM F136 material certificate values."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties must be sourced from traceable coupon testing or peer-reviewed literature. Geometric dimensions must be measured from the actual test articles using calibrated metrology equipment with documented uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V ELI screws and rods were obtained from coupon tensile tests performed on specimens machined from the same billet stock as the implants (certificate of conformance on file). UHMWPE block properties were taken from ISO 5834-2 reference data. Screw and rod geometry was measured using a Zeiss Contura CMM (calibration certificate valid through 2024-06); dimensional deviations from nominal CAD were less than 0.03 mm across all 11 constructs and were propagated into the model as per-replicate geometry adjustments."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A minimum of N=10 test constructs must be included across at least two independent laboratories. Sample traceability (lot, sterilization batch, assembly torque) must be documented for each construct.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were tested: six at FDA CDRH laboratory and five at an independent contract laboratory (Empirical Testing Corporation, Austin TX). All constructs were assembled from the same manufacturing lot (lot 2023-07-A), sterilized in a single EO cycle, and assembled to the manufacturer-specified set-screw torque (4.0 Nm ± 0.1 Nm, verified with a calibrated torque wrench). Full traceability records are maintained in the study master file SMF-COU1-2023."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span at least two clinically relevant load magnitudes or offset distances to characterize the model's response surface. Single-condition testing is acceptable only if supported by sensitivity analysis demonstrating linearity of QoI response across the anticipated clinical range.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted exclusively at the ASTM F1717 standard offset distance (60 mm) and at a single crosshead displacement rate (25 mm/min). While this condition is the regulatory standard for pedicle screw construct evaluation, it represents only one point on the load-offset response surface. A sensitivity analysis was performed varying the offset distance from 40 mm to 80 mm in the FEA model; stiffness varied by 18% and yield force by 12% across this range, indicating non-trivial sensitivity. The single-condition experimental dataset therefore achieves Gradation 2 rather than the required Gradation 3. This shortfall is acknowledged and is the primary driver of the Medium assurance level assigned to COU1. Future work should include testing at a minimum of two offset distances to elevate this factor to the required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All simulation boundary conditions must be demonstrably equivalent to the experimental setup, with documented mapping of each experimental fixture constraint to its FEA representation. Any deviations must be quantified via sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 fixture was reverse-engineered from the test laboratory drawings and implemented in the FEA model as rigid constraint surfaces with the identical offset geometry. Potting material (PMMA) stiffness was measured from four companion specimens and applied as a homogeneous isotropic elastic layer. A sensitivity study on potting stiffness (±20% from measured mean) produced less than 0.8% variation in all three QoIs, confirming that the equivalency is not materially affected by potting uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Comparison must use a validation metric that accounts for experimental uncertainty. The E/uval ratio (ASME V&V 10.1) must be below 1.96 for each QoI. Percentage difference between mean FEA prediction and mean experimental result must be below 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "The validation comparison was performed using the E/uval metric per ASME V&V 10.1. Experimental uncertainty was quantified as the combined standard uncertainty from repeat measurements, load cell calibration, and displacement transducer calibration. Results: stiffness E/uval = 1.41 (6.3% difference), yield force E/uval = 1.18 (4.9% difference), force at 40 mm E/uval = 0.87 (3.2% difference). All three QoIs pass both the E/uval < 1.96 and <10% difference criteria."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Each QoI must be directly linked to a clinical failure mode or regulatory acceptance criterion. The linkage must be documented in a QoI relevance matrix cross-referencing the COU intended use statement.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were selected: construct stiffness (linked to subsidence and adjacent-level effects), yield force (linked to implant fatigue initiation under cyclic in vivo loading), and force at 40 mm displacement (the ASTM F1717 regulatory acceptance metric). A QoI relevance matrix in the study protocol SP-COU1-2023 cross-references each QoI to its clinical failure mode and to the specific clause of the 510(k) submission that relies on the FEA prediction."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario must be demonstrated to be representative of the COU with respect to geometry, loading mode, boundary conditions, and material system. Any differences between the validation scenario and the COU must be explicitly enumerated and shown to be conservative or negligible.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the regulatory submission scenario: the same 7.5 mm non-cannulated screw design, the same ASTM F1717 test configuration, and the same material system are used in both the validation experiments and the COU FEA predictions. The only difference is that the validation uses a single offset distance while the COU encompasses the full clinical range; this difference is addressed under the Test Conditions factor and is the basis for the Medium assurance level. No other material differences exist between the validation scenario and the COU."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/fda-cdrh-osel-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors achieve the required gradation level. One factor (Test conditions) achieves Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3, reflecting the single-condition experimental dataset. This shortfall is mitigated by the FEA sensitivity analysis demonstrating bounded QoI variation across the clinical offset range, and by the strength of the output comparison results (all E/uval < 1.96). The overall credibility is assessed as Medium, consistent with the model risk level of 3 and the Medium model influence and decision consequence. The package is accepted for use in the 510(k) submission with the noted limitation on test condition coverage.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
